# Killswitch

> **Status:** ACTIVE
>
> **Last updated:** YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM (TZ)
>
> **Last halt reason:** —

---

## What this file is

Every agent in the stack reads this file as the first step of every non-trivial action. If `Status` above is set to `HALT`, the agent must stop immediately, log the halt, and exit cleanly without performing further writes, API calls, or side effects.

This is the operator's last-line brake. It is reachable without authentication, without admin consoles, and without remembering which credentials belong to which agent. One file, one edit, one git commit — and every agent in the stack stops at its next read.

## How to invoke a halt

1. Open this file.
2. Change `Status: ACTIVE` to `Status: HALT`.
3. Update `Last updated` to the current timestamp.
4. Set `Last halt reason` to a one-line description of why you are halting (the *why* matters for incident-log reconstruction later).
5. Commit the change to git.

The agents will pick up the halt on their next read of this file. If an agent is mid-operation when the halt is committed, it will complete the in-flight step and exit before starting the next step — there is no kill-the-process-mid-write semantic here, because that would create exactly the kind of half-written state the framework is trying to avoid.

## How to recover

1. Investigate the cause of the halt. Read the relevant agent logs, the vault state at halt time, and any external systems that may have been affected.
2. Fix the underlying issue — code change, configuration change, credential rotation, whatever the investigation surfaces.
3. Update this file: change `Status: HALT` back to `Status: ACTIVE`, update `Last updated`, and set `Last halt reason` to a one-line description of what was found and fixed (preserve the prior reason in a recovery note below if useful).
4. Commit the change.
5. Re-enable any agents that were paused at the halt; they will read the now-ACTIVE killswitch on their next invocation and resume.

## Convention notes for adopters

- **Do not delete this file** even when no halts have occurred. Agents are configured to fail-closed: if the killswitch file is missing, the agent halts as if it found a HALT directive. The convention is that the file always exists.
- **Do not edit `Last halt reason` to clear the history** when going from HALT back to ACTIVE. The git history is the audit trail; if you want a clean current-state representation, use a separate "halt log" file in `00-meta/` to capture incident details, and keep `Last halt reason` as just the most recent.
- **Never let the killswitch live somewhere agents would not read it.** The path `00-meta/killswitch.md` is the convention; if you change the path, every agent's configuration changes too.

